<TEI xmlns="http://www.tei-c.org/ns/1.0" xmlns:frus="http://history.state.gov/frus/ns/1.0"><text><body><div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1938-06-04T09:00:00-05:00" frus:doc-dateTime-min="1938-06-04T09:00:00-05:00" n="842" subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d842">
                            <note rend="inline" type="source">890D.00/697: Telegram</note>
                            <head><hi rend="italic">The Consul General at Beirut</hi> (<persName type="from"><hi rend="italic">Palmer</hi></persName>) <hi rend="italic">to the <gloss type="to">Secretary of
                                    State</gloss></hi></head>
                            <opener>
                                <dateline rendition="#right"><placeName><hi rend="smallcaps">Beirut</hi></placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1938-06-04T16:00:00+02:00">June 4, 1938—4
                                    p.m.</date><lb/>[Received June 5—11 a.m.]</dateline>
                            </opener>
                            <p>Department’s June 3, 7 p.m. Farrell left yesterday with <hi rend="italic">laissez passer</hi> obtained through the High
                                Commission. I have notified Embassy at Ankara that his address is as
                                follows: Princeton Expedition, Antioch. He reports situation calm
                                today and that Commandant Collet, as officer responsible for public
                                security, promises to notify Americans if emergency makes their
                                departure advisable.</p>
                            <closer><signed><hi rend="smallcaps">Palmer</hi></signed></closer>
                        </div>
                        </body></text></TEI>